<h3><span class=3D"mw-headline" id=3D"pacman_crashes_the_official_installat=
ion_media">pacman crashes the official installation media</span></h3>
<p>The official installation media (ISO) before version 10.2015 are not set=
up to be updated itself at runtime. Running <code>pacman -Syu</code> from a=
 booted install media console may crash unexpectedly any time, as soon as m=
emory is depleted. This happens because the install media image build repor=
ts an arbitrary capacity (of 32GB) to pacman, regardless of available free =
memory.<a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external autonumber" href=3D"https://bu=
gs.archlinux.org/task/45618#comment137346">[1]</a> At the same time the ISO=
 reserves only a low static memory allotment for operations (<code>/run/arc=
hiso/cowspace</code> of <code>256MB</code> RAM) of the live system, in orde=
r to allow installation on machines with low resources. If the machine has =
more RAM available, you can override the allotment by setting the <code>cow=
_spacesize=3D</code> kernel option for the ISO manually, e.g. <code>cow_spa=
cesize=3D2GB</code>. =20
</p><p>If you use the install media to update an installed system, you simp=
ly have to use the <code>--root=3D</code> option along with a <code>--cache=
dir=3D</code> path to point pacman to available real storage. For example, =
see <a href=3D"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Pacman_(%E7%AE%80%E4%BD=
%93%E4%B8%AD%E6%96%87)#pacman_.E6.9B.B4.E6.96.B0.E6.97.B6.E5.B4.A9.E6.BA.83=
">#pacman =E6=9B=B4=E6=96=B0=E6=97=B6=E5=B4=A9=E6=BA=83</a>.=20
</p><p>If you <i>require</i> an install media with persistent dataspace, th=
e <a href=3D"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Archiso" title=3D"Archiso=
">Archiso</a> build script can be used to create one along with its <a rel=
=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://projects.archlinux.or=
g/archiso.git/tree/docs/README.bootparams">boot options</a>.
</p>
